idea of Mennonite food became a way of maintaining community identity, even as unfamiliar environments obliged Mennonites to borrow and learn from their neighbours. Looking at Mennonites past and present, Epp shows that foodstuffs (cuisine) and foodways (practices) depend on historical and cultural context. She explores how diets have evolved as a result of migration, settlement, and mission; how food and gender identities relate to both power and fear; how cookbooks and recipes are full of social meaning; how experiences and memories of food scarcity shape identity; and how food is an expression of religious beliefs – as a symbol, in ritual, and in acts of charity.From zwieback to tamales and from sauerkraut to spring rolls, Eating Like a Mennonite reveals food as a complex ingredient in ethnic, religious, and personal identities, with the ability to create both bonds and boundaries between people.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFood-Religious aspects-Mennonites. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Mennonite.2bisacsh  aAnabaptists.  aCanada.  aCongo.  aIndia.  aIndigenous.  aLaos.  aMexico.  aParaguay.  aPennsylvania.  aRussia.  aSwiss.  aUkraine.  aacculturation.  aadaptation.  abread.  acanning.  achurch.  acommunity.  acookbooks.  acooking.  acuisine.  aculinary.  aculture.  aeating.  aethnicity.  aethnography.  afamine.  agarden.  agender.  aimmigration.  amasculinity.  amemoir.  amemory.  amissionary.  amothers.  anonbinary.  apotlucks.  arecipes.  arefugees.  areligion.  aritual.  asettlement.  astarvation.  atrauma.  awomen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packagez978